    { "id": "mw", "type": "security", "label": "Rate Limiter", "sublabel": "middleware", "pos": [260, 120], "size": [140, 64], "tag": "100 / min" },
    { "id": "redis", "type": "database", "label": "Redis", "sublabel": "sliding window", "pos": [260, 280], "size": [140, 60] },
    { "id": "handler", "type": "backend", "label": "API Handler", "sublabel": "business logic", "pos": [500, 120], "size": [140, 60] }
  ],
  "connections": [
    { "from": "client", "to": "mw", "label": "request", "variant": "emphasis" },
    { "from": "mw", "to": "redis", "label": "INCR / EXPIRE", "variant": "security", "fromSide": "bottom", "toSide": "top" },
    { "from": "mw", "to": "handler", "label": "under limit" }
  ]
}
```

## Approach

A middleware checks a sliding-window counter before the handler runs:

```typescript
export async function rateLimit(req: Req, res: Res, next: Next) {
  const key = `rl:${req.token}:${currentMinute()}`
  const hits = await redis.incr(key)
  if (hits === 1) await redis.expire(key, 60)
  if (hits > LIMIT) {
    res.setHeader('Retry-After', secondsToNextMinute())
    return res.status(429).json({ error: 'rate_limited' })
  }
  next()
}
```

## Decision flow

A small auto-laid-out decision → Mermaid is the right tool here (no need for Archify's explicit layout):

```mermaid
graph TD
  A[request] --> B{hits > limit?}
  B -->|no| C[handler]
  B -->|yes| D[429 + Retry-After]
```

## Tasks

- [x] Redis counter helper
- [ ] Middleware + wiring
- [ ] `429` + `Retry-After`
- [ ] Load test at the boundary

## Acceptance

| Requirement | Check |
|---|---|
| 100 req/min per token | integration test bursts 120 → 20× `429` |
| Shared across instances | two nodes, one token, combined cap holds |
| `Retry-After` present | header equals seconds to next minute |

:::details[Alternatives considered]
- **In-memory counter** — rejected: not shared across instances.
- **Token bucket** — deferred: smoother but more state; revisit if bursts hurt.
- **Sliding-window log** — rejected: per-request memory cost too high at scale.
:::
